Persistence assay analysis

2022-09-30

Info

Rmarkdown report for the analysis to go with the manuscript “Biofilms preserve the transmissibility of a multi-drug resistance plasmid” by Genevieve A. Metzger, Benjamin J. Ridenhour, Michael France, Karol Gliniewicz, Jack Millstein, Matthew L. Settles, Larry J. Forney, Thibault Stalder, and Eva M. Top.

Data processing steps performed under ‘Data processing’:

  1. Model description
  2. Import and prepare persistence assays data
  3. Persistence assays of evolved clones
  1. Persistence assays of the Ancestor and T0
  2. Persistence assays of the clones evolved withOUT selection
  3. Persistence assays of the clones evolved with selection
  1. Persistence assays of truncated and full-length plasmids
  1. Persistence assays of evolved plasmids types tested in their co-evolved hosts
  2. Persistence assays of evolved plasmids types tested into the ancestral host background

1) Model description

Model use is a linear mixed-effects model where the log plasmid:chromosome ratio of each group was predicted using the origin of the clones (i.e., t0, biofilm, or planktonic population) or the type of plasmid tested (i.e., truncated vs full-length) as fixed effect and the clone replicate measure as random effect. Each parameter was nested within the day of the experiment (Days 0, 5, 8) as a continuous variable.

#subset columns
analysisData = cNo[,c("Ancestor","Colony","Day", "ColonyID", "ratio", "ratio.se", "Clone.Number", "Plasmid.size", "mutated")]

#Generate a dataframe with the clones
tempData = data.frame(Ancestor = names(Environment))
tempData$Ancestor = as.character(tempData$Ancestor)
tempData$Environment = Environment[tempData$Ancestor]
tempData$Timepoint = Timepoint[tempData$Ancestor]
tempData$Experiment = Experiment[tempData$Ancestor]
analysisData = merge(analysisData,tempData)
rm(tempData)

#add new environment value that includes Abr status
analysisData$EnvExp = paste(analysisData$Environment, analysisData$Experiment)
analysisData$EnvExp = as.factor(analysisData$EnvExp)
analysisData$EnvExp = relevel(analysisData$EnvExp, ref = "Anc NA")

analysisData$Environment = as.factor(analysisData$Environment)

3) Persistence assays of evolved clones

A) Persistence assays of the Ancestor and T0

  • Focus on the ancestor (t-4) and clones isolated from all the biofilms harvested at time t0
  • Results show that plasmid persistence dynamics of the ancestor and the T0 were similar.

Model

#Selected the dataset
analysisData$EnvExp = relevel(analysisData$EnvExp, ref = "Anc NA")
setT0_Anc = analysisData$Environment %in% c("Starting", "Anc") & analysisData$Day %in% c(0,5,8) & analysisData$Timepoint %in% c(-4, 0)

#The model
fullModel.T0_Anc = lme(log(ratio)~Day/EnvExp,random=~1+Day|ColonyID,data=analysisData,subset=setT0_Anc)
vals2_T0_Anc = unique(analysisData[setT0_Anc,c("Day","EnvExp")])
vals2_T0_Anc$predicted = exp(predict(fullModel.T0_Anc, vals2_T0_Anc, level = 0))

summary(fullModel.T0_Anc)

Plot

p4_A = ggplot(data=analysisData[setT0_Anc,],aes(x=Day,y=ratio, color=EnvExp))
p4_A = p4_A +
  geom_point(position=position_dodge(w=0.35),size=1) +
  geom_line(data=vals2_T0_Anc,aes(x=Day,y=predicted, color=EnvExp, linetype = EnvExp)) +
  scale_y_continuous(trans = "log10", breaks = theBreaks, labels = theLabels, limits = c(0.00000000005,100)) + 
  ylab(expression(paste("Plasmid:chromosome ratio"))) + 
  xlab(expression("Time (days)")) + 
  scale_color_manual(name="Time Point",
                     breaks=c("Anc NA", "Starting Abr+","Starting Abr-"),
                     labels=c(expression("Ancestor"),
                              expression(Tet+ ~ italic(t)["0"]),
                              expression(Tet- ~ italic(t)["0"])),
                     values=c("#000000","#636363","#bdbdbd")) + 
  scale_linetype_manual(values = c("solid", "dashed","dotted")) +
  theme

B) Persistence assays of the clones evolved withOUT selection

  • Focus on the clones isolated from each time point of the Tet- evolution experiment.
  • Results show a drastic increase in plasmid persistence in planktonic populations but not in biofilm populations.

4) Persistence assays of truncated and full-length plasmids

A) Persistence assays of evolved plasmids types tested in their co-evolved hosts

  • Focus on the effect of the large plasmid sequence deletions in their co-evolved hosts.
  • Results show truncated plasmids had a higher plasmid persistence than clones with full-length plasmids.
set_LDvAvU = analysisData$Environment %in% c("Starting", "Biofilm", "Liquid", "Anc") & analysisData$Day %in% c(0,5,8) & analysisData$Timepoint %in% c(-4, 0, 6, 10, 14, 28) & analysisData$mutated %in% c("anc", "largedel", "unchanged")

Model

analysisData$mutated = factor(analysisData$mutated, level = c("largedel", "anc","unchanged","smalldel","snp"))
fullModel.LDvAvU = lme(log(ratio)~Day/mutated,random=~1+Day|ColonyID,data=analysisData,subset=set_LDvAvU) #control=lmeControl(msMaxIter = 500))
vals2_LDvAvU = unique(analysisData[set_LDvAvU,c("Day","mutated")])
vals2_LDvAvU$predicted = exp(predict(fullModel.LDvAvU, vals2_LDvAvU, level = 0))

B) Persistence assays of evolved plasmids types tested into the ancestral host background

  • Results show that plasmid persistence was higher for the truncated plasmids than for the full-length plasmid or ancestral pB10.
